    value: 息
english:
  title: The Flute That Stills Ten Thousand Waves
  author: Yu Ho-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Six whales rise in the east of Silla's domain,
    Where ocean winds bellow and clouds stretch ten thousand miles.
    Through the haze, a single lotus blooms in jade,
    An ancient dragon bears it up from the palace deep.

    Bamboo shoots forth above, trembling and slight,
    Its lonely shadow shivers in the dawn moon's light.
    The king once left his golden hall of state,
    And stopped his royal chariot by the sea's curved gate.

    When they cut the sacred root, the great earth shook,
    And lightning flashed—the heavens darkened with a look.
    They returned and carved sixteen holes with care,
    And from it flowed a song like phoenixes in air.

    Before the Sea-View Hall, with just a few brief notes,
    Auspicious winds swept clean all evil's floating motes.
    In times of peace, beneath the moon of Chicken Forest spring,
    The bells rang out and tripods held the feasts of emperors and kings.

    Five hundred years the seasons blessed the land,
    And elders sang of peace in every village and each strand.
    Yet pity—successors could not hold the sacred trust,
    And foolishly relied on talismans that turned to dust.

    At last the lord and courtiers gave way to wine,
    And at the Stone Pavilion, storm winds crossed the line.
    The heavenly mandate could not be reclaimed,
    And on Gold Whale Mountain, sunset burned in shame.

    Though your noble name meant "waves at peace,"
    O jade flute, how can suffering ever cease?
    What fate awaits you now?
  footnotes:
    - The 'Six Whales' refers to the legend that Korea stands on six whales; 'Silla' refers to the ancient Korean kingdom of Unified Silla (668-935).
    - This poem laments the fall of Unified Silla, which ended in 935. The flute described here is legendary—the Manpasikjeok (萬波息笛), said to be created during the reign of King Munmu and capable of stilling troubled waters and bringing peace.
    - The 'Stone Pavilion' (Poseokjeong) is where the last Silla king reportedly drowned, symbolizing the dynasty's collapse.
    - The poem contrasts a golden age of five centuries under Silla with its ultimate downfall due to failed leadership and moral decline.
